gender_counts = df['Gender'].value_counts()     

gender_percentages = gender_counts / len(df) * 100    

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

bars = plt.bar(gender_counts.index, gender_counts, color=['blue', 'pink'])      

for bar, percentage in zip(bars, gender_percentages):
    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, yval + 5, f"{percentage:.1f}%", ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.title('Distribution of Genders Among Employees')
plt.xlabel('Gender')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Employees')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)                                                    
plt.show()

# Calculating the average age
average_age = df['Age'].mean()

# Plotting the age distribution using a histogram

plt.hist(df['Age'], bins=20, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')  

# Adding a vertical line for the average age

plt.title('Age Distribution of Employees')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Number of Employees')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Counting the number of employees in each department
department_counts = df['DepartmentName'].value_counts()

# Plotting the distribution using a bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
bars = plt.bar(department_counts.index, department_counts, color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')

# Display the exact number on top of each bar
for bar, count in zip(bars, department_counts):
    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, yval + 5, f"{count}", ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.title('Distribution of Employees Across Different Departments')
plt.xlabel('Department')
plt.ylabel('Number of Employees')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  
plt.show()
In [98]:
# Selectecting specific departments 
selected_departments = ['Customer Service', 'Dairy', 'Meats', 'Bakery', 'Processed Foods', 'Produce']
department_order = ['Customer Service', 'Dairy', 'Meats', 'Bakery', 'Processed Foods', 'Produce']

# Filterring the data for the selected departments
selected_df = df[df['DepartmentName'].isin(selected_departments)]

# Calculating the total absence hours for each department
total_absence_hours = selected_df.groupby('DepartmentName')['AbsentHours'].sum().sort_values()

# Calculating the average absence hours per employee for each department
average_absence_per_employee = selected_df.groupby('DepartmentName')['AbsentHours'].sum() / selected_df.groupby('DepartmentName')['EmployeeNumber'].nunique()

# Setting colors for each department
department_colors = {
    'Customer Service': 'blue',
    'Dairy': 'orange',
    'Meats': 'green',
    'Bakery': 'red',
    'Processed Foods': 'purple',
    'Produce': 'brown'
}

# Creating subplots 1x2
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(20, 10))

# Plot the total absence hours with consistent colors and order
sns.barplot(ax=axes[0], x=total_absence_hours.index, y=total_absence_hours, order=department_order, palette=[department_colors[dept] for dept in department_order])
axes[0].set_title('Total Absence Hours in Selected Departments')
axes[0].set_xlabel('Department')
axes[0].set_ylabel('Total Absence Hours')
axes[0].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

# Plot the average absence hours per employee with consistent colors and order
sns.barplot(ax=axes[1], x=average_absence_per_employee.index, y=average_absence_per_employee, order=department_order, palette=[department_colors[dept] for dept in department_order])
axes[1].set_title('Average Absence Hours Per Employee in Selected Departments')
axes[1].set_xlabel('Department')
axes[1].set_ylabel('Average Absence Hours Per Employee')
axes[1].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

# Adjusting layout to prevent overlapping
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
